{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17516876","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17516876"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:47:46+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:47:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12726"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12726","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12726"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.17,0.1,0.09,0.19,0.44]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5181"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111174"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5181","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5181"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12726"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93301"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"6549"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8776"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8934"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14604"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35899"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111174","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111174"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 75-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with confusion. He has a medical history of type 2 diabetes mellitus (recent haemoglobin A1c of 9%) and end-stage renal failure requiring haemodialysis three times per week. He was recently admitted to hospital for community-acquired pneumonia, requiring seven days of intravenous antibiotics and a brief intensive care admission. He does not take any regular medications other than insulin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 115/min, blood pressure 80/55 mmHg, respiratory rate 25/min, SpO2 88% on room air, and temperature 38.5\u00b0C. There is an infected diabetic ulcer on his left foot.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe patient is treated with oxygen via face mask, intravenous access is established, and empirical antibiotics are commenced.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhite cell count: 12.2 x 10^9/L (3.6-11.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemoglobin: 120 g/L (130-180)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELactate: 2.8 mmol/L (0.5-2.2)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThree blood cultures taken from different sites demonstrate gram-positive cocci resembling \u003Cem\u003EStaphylococcus\u003C/em\u003E after six hours of growth.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following antibiotic combinations is most appropriate?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Benzylpenicillin, flucloxacillin, and gentamicin","Ceftriaxone and metronidazole","Amoxicillin and gentamicin","Amoxicillin and clavulanate","Vancomycin, piperacillin and tazobactam"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn sepsis management, early and appropriate antibiotic therapy is crucial. The choice of antibiotics should be based on the likely pathogens, considering the patient\u0027s risk factors and local resistance patterns. This is a case of septic shock with the infected diabetic foot ulcer as the probable source. Diabetic foot infections are commonly polymicrobial. Common organisms include \u003Cem\u003EStaphylococcus aureus\u003C/em\u003E, gram-negative bacteria (e.g., \u003Cem\u003EPseudomonas aeruginosa\u003C/em\u003E, \u003Cem\u003EEnterococcus\u003C/em\u003E spp), and anaerobes. Given his recent hospitalisation and haemodialysis dependence, there is a high risk of methicillin-resistant \u003Cem\u003EStaphylococcus aureus\u003C/em\u003E (MRSA) infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVancomycin, piperacillin and tazobactam\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate antibiotic combination in this case. Piperacillin and tazobactam is the recommended empirical therapy for severe diabetic foot infection. It offers broad-spectrum coverage for gram-negative organisms, including \u003Cem\u003EPseudomonas aeruginosa\u003C/em\u003E. However, this patient has a severe infection and is at increased risk of MRSA infection, hence the addition of vancomycin should be considered.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAmoxicillin and clavulanate\u003C/strong\u003E provides broad-spectrum coverage against many gram-positive and gram-negative bacteria, including some strains of \u003Cem\u003EStaphylococcus aureus\u003C/em\u003E. However, it is not effective against MRSA. It can be used for empirical therapy of non-severe diabetic foot infection. Given the severity of this case, and the increased risk of MRSA infection, this combination would not be suitable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBenzylpenicillin, flucloxacillin, and gentamicin\u003C/strong\u003E would not provide adequate coverage for MRSA. This combination is used for empirical treatment of native valve infective endocarditis. While this combination may be effective against MSSA and some gram-negative organisms, it would not be sufficient for a patient with high risk of MRSA infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECeftriaxone and metronidazole\u003C/strong\u003E would not be appropriate for suspected staphylococcal sepsis. This combination is used in some cases of intra-abdominal infections, such as severe diverticulitis and acute appendicitis. Ceftriaxone may be effective against MSSA but not MRSA, and metronidazole targets anaerobic bacteria, which are not suspected in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAmoxicillin and gentamicin\u003C/strong\u003E would not provide adequate coverage for MRSA. This combination is used for the empirical therapy of severe pyelonephritis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Patients with sepsis and septic shock require urgent provision of antibiotics.","MRSA is an increasingly common infection that may be hospital-acquired, and may cause sepsis.","Vancomycin is commonly used to treat MRSA infections.","Piperacillin and tazobactam is commonly used for the empirical treatment of severe diabetic foot infection."],"references":["Armstrong DG, Tan TW, Boulton AJM, Bus SA. Diabetic Foot Ulcers: A Review. JAMA. 2023 Jul 3;330(1):62\u201375. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/37395769/","Reardon R, Simring D, Kim B, Mortensen J, Williams D, Leslie A. The diabetic foot ulcer. Australian Journal for General Practitioners. 2020 May 1;49:250\u20135. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/32416652/","Antibiotic [published 2019 April]. In: Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited; accessed {24th Aug 2024}. https://www.tg.org.au"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93301"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12726"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93301","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93301"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-09T20:52:11+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-09T20:52:29+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5181"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111174"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"gr